Huawei Technologies has expressed concerns over the proposed United States (US) restriction on chip-making equipment, saying that it would adversely affect Africa. This was disclosed by the director of Media Affairs, Huawei Southern Africa Region, Edison Xie. He said that the new measure would also restrict the global supply of chips to Huawei Technologies, at a time when the COVID-19 pandemic impacts economic growth around the world. Under the proposed rule change, foreign companies that use American chip-making equipment would be required to obtain a US license before supplying certain chips to Huawei. In 2019, the global market for semiconductors was projected to shrink by 12 per cent due to growing economic uncertainties from the US-China trade war. This year’s COVID-19 pandemic is further shaking up the global semiconductor industry. A new IDC report says that the semiconductor industry will fall by six per cent The proposed move by some US officials will create more uncertainties